title: For Sale:  Remington 870 Police Magnum - NOT an Express shotgun
postcontent:
This is NOT a Remington Express gun - this is Police Magnum, which is much more durable!

Remington Police Magnums come with a parkerized finish on an 18" barrel (as opposed to a Blued finish on an Express); feature a stronger sear spring and magazine spring; better extractor and ejector, and much more.

Shotgun has rifle sights and has been gone over completely by in-house Remington LE Certified Armorer. This shotgun goes for $650 new in the box if your are Law Enforcement.

While the 870 Express is still an 870, the best pump shotgun on the market, there are some very important cosmetic and functional differences between it and the 870 Police. To our customers in Law Enforcement, Military, Corrections, and Security, whose lives depend upon the unfailing performance of Remington shotguns, the Police modifications are of paramount importance.

Synopses of the variances are provided below.
870 Police shotguns go thru a special 23 station check list – ranging from visual inspection, functional testing, test firing, and final inspection.
All Police shotguns are assembled in a “special build area” at the plant in Ilion, NY. This section is secured and serves only to build LE and Military shotguns, with the same factory personnel working at that assignment each shift.
All parts that enter the “special build area” are visually inspected by hand to ensure top quality and functionality.
Due to heavy recoil in buck and slug loads, all 870 Police guns have a longer magazine spring which ensures positive feed and function.
A heavier sear spring is used to generate a reliable, positive trigger pull between 5 and 8 lbs.
A heavier carrier dog spring is used to ensure when the carrier elevates the shell, it will be held there until the bolt can push it into the chamber. This ensures positive feeding when using heavier payload rounds.
Police shotguns do not have an ISS (Integrated Safety System) which is a locking mechanism on the safety of commercial shotguns. This type of locking mechanism can cause delay to an officer who needs the weapon but does not have the appropriate key. LE shotguns have the standard, proven, cross bolt safety.
The fore-end on the Express model is longer and not compatible with many police shotgun vehicle racks. The Police shotguns utilize the heavy duty SPEEDFEED Stocks and Fore-ends.
The Express model will not allow for the addition of an extension tube without physical modification to the tube and barrel, which can nullify the warranty.
The Express model has a BEAD BLAST BLUE finish while the Police models utilize Parkerization. The Express model utilizes a synthetic trigger housing while the Police models use a compressed metal housing.
The Police shotgun barrel is locked down with a “ball detent” system in conjunction with the magazine cap vs. a lesser grade “synthetic magazine spring retainer” lock down as used on the Express system.
The receivers used in Police guns are “vibra honed” to smooth out rough finishes and remove burrs before parkerization.
Police shotguns use machined ejectors and extractors, as opposed to powdered metal cast which are utilized on the Express models.


$500.
Not interested in trades.
Requires FFL transfer.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester USGI M1 Carbine W/NEW USGI BARREL, Wood and Polymer stocks
postcontent:
Winchester M1 Carbine has a NEW USGI Winchester barrel that was installed this year and only has a couple magazines ran through it, the barrel has not even been broken in. As shown it is fitted in a Choate Tool folding stock with a plumbed Ultimak Optics rail hand guard system. As includes a New USGI type Overton breech wood stock and hand guard, with oiler and sling(not photoed). 6 US made 30 round magazines, 8 Korean 30 round magazines, dust covers, pouches, and various USGI 15 round magazines. MAY include vacuum packed FMJ ammo in USGI bandolier with stripper clips with some offers.

The new barrel is a new unused and unissued USGI Winchester barrel through Riverbank Armory. Has been install properly to assure good head space and front to rear sight timing. The bore the tightest, cleanest that I have ever seen on a M1 Carbine. It was well worth the investment, makes the Winchester M1 Carbine a whole new machine it seems.


Sorry no picture of carbine in wood stock. To do so I would have to remove the sight rail which I have plumbed ( in line with the sight group and receiver). You all know what a M1 Carbine looks like with wood stocks anyway. I'll take pictures of the wood stocks for those interested. Their new, in great shape.

This is a USGI made M1 Carbine, made with forged steel and all USGI or US parts(minus the Korean mags). The upgrades are the polymer with steel reinforced stock mated with the Ultkmak aluminum optics rail. No changes or modification have been made to the carbine other then changing the stocks. The wood stocks are breech and by Overton. Changing the stocks can be done in minutes. The the Ultimak rail can be used with the wood stock. With the new USGI barrel it is very accurate. The optics rail and polymer folding stock are great enhancements to this carbine. This is not a soft steel Universal or other brand production. Loaded with modern HP ammo the .30 carbine is an excellent round in a small package

No import stamps, all new springs, all parts fit well, barrel passes head space on GO. No rust, Parkerizing is in good shape. Normal wear, no damage. NO CASH VALUE HAS BEEN DETERMINED ON THIS FIREARM AT THIS TIME.

Only reason I'm considering trading this firearm is that it isn't as condusive to left handed rifle shooting as other platforms.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 30.06 I bolt with a Nikon Buckmaster 4.5-14x40mm
postcontent:
Right Handed Smith & Wesson I bolt:
Thompson Center barrel, very lite rifle, great recoil pad, Timmney designed adjustable trigger down to 3lbs I believe. Realtree camo stock design. 
This gun groups amazing with Remington Core-Lokts, I tried 165 and 180grain bullets. At 100yds with the 165 Grains I had 3/4 inch 3 shot group for the first 3 shots and for the 2nd 3 shot group I was still under an inch. I  believe If I had been using my Caldwell rest and not a table and a jacket as a rest it would have been more consistent and tighter.  It comes with the following:
Super sling: $18 Walmart
Weaver Rings: $15.00
S&W: Plastic and foam lined gun case.
Nikon Buchmaster: 4.5-14x40mm with Adjustable parallax. I was around $320 new at Cabelas + shipping. Scope is in excellent condition. Possibly a tiny brush scratch but optics are perfect! I would give the scope a 9.5 out of 10. As well as the gun. A tiny bit of paint blurring on the bolt workings and inside of action.

With listed extras this gun Was over $850 dollars. I ordered this gun new through a FFL gunsmith from a gun distributor who had them on sale brand new. I paid $450 which was over $250 off the original retail price.

I am wanting $625 obo, 
Already over a $225 dollar loss from the original purchases prices of gun and accessories. I am okay with that loss and am willing to do trade or part trade on Silver, gold,(at spot,) possibly ammo, other firearms. I would like a 10/22 preferably older models but I am flexible, also looking for AK, AR,  Mossy 500 defense or tactical, .357, .38, Taurus 1911, other 1911. I have cash and 17 morgan silver dollars and a couple other guns to add to the right trade if there is a diffence in value and I am interested. Open to other offers, run it by me. 

My only complaint about this rifle is that it only feeds reliably with 3 cartridges in it. It can hold 4+1 but the way the shells stack in the mag well it appears that they line up incorrectly with more than 3 in the gun and the bolt attempts to bypass the cartridge or occasionally double load when you have 4 or 5 in the gun. 
However, I didn't mind hunting with three cartridges and I read that maybe it will change as the spring is used and broken in or it will cycle better with different cartridges or handloads? 

text, email, or call:
541-Nine7three-7fourEight7

title: For Sale:  Federal HST .40S&W JHP - 100 round lots/up to 800rds
postcontent:
Best CCW Ammo you can buy!

For sale is 100 rounds of Federal HST 155gr JHP for a .40S&W. 
I do have more of this ammunition if you would like up to 800 rounds.

Federal released its Hydra-Shok line of ammunition to capture the law enforcement market years ago, and while it was a good round - it proved troublesome when going through barriers before reaching its target - clogging much of the time.

Federal corrected the problem by introducing a line known as HST, and it was tested extensively by the FBI upon its release in .40 caliber, and adopted as their ammunition after blowing the tests out of the water. This is currently the only ammunition I will carry as I feel like it is the only ammunition to hold a candle to the famous "Black Talon".

It's easy to find the much less desirable Hydra-Shok ammunition on the shelf, and many people are intrigued by the "post" inside the hollow point. If you do the research, and I suggest you do, you will find that HST is extremely tough to beat.

That's why HST has almost never (in my experience) been for sale on the shelves at your local gun shop - I have only ever found it online, for a premium price, and in small or limited quantities. I have recently switched to a different caliber for my preferred CCW and cannot find anywhere that sells HST in bulk, must less a place with a single box in stock right now.

I live in Puyallup, but will be willing to drive a reasonable distance to meet - or even ship if you want to pay for shipping.

Take a look here for FBI Protocol test results on this ammunition
http://le.atk.com/ammunition/federal/handgun/details.aspx?id=567

title: For Sale:  NEPALESE GAHENDRA MARTINI-HENRY RIFLE (577/450)
postcontent:
The Martini-Henry Gahendra was based on an 1869 Westley Richards patented design, this unique and extremely rare early breechloading Military Rifle 577/450 Martini-Henry calibre was produced under the direction of General Gahendra Rana in the 1880's to provide Ghurka regiments with what appeared to be the latest British Military Rifle. An ingenious design, it really surpassed the standard Martini in that its entire action was removable as one unit for ease of servicing or exchange. Production however caused massive logistic problems and by 1894 the Ghurkas were dangerously short of viable .450 cal. breechloaders to face ever growing threats from the east. Finally the British came to the rescue with a delivery of several thousand Martini short lever rifles in late 1894 and even more long lever Martini Rifles in 1908. The over complicated Gahendra Rifle was thereafter basically shelved, the void in up-to-date arms having been met. Always considered the rarest Martini variety of all, the Gahendra Rifle has a characteristic loading lever but in other respects closely resembles the standard Martini externally.
Comes with Bayonet in good clean condition  will accept reasonable offers.
